15. tn Aquitaniam that is, to sweep the country lrom the Loire to the Garonne, and thenis necessary, to cross the latter river into Aqui· tanin. The Aquitanians were (except the Bituriges) os such a different stock from the Belgae and Armoricans, that they were not likely to join their consederacy. But Caesar probably did not know this: and thus the present may have seemed to him a favourable opportunity lor pushing his arms into the only part ol Gaul to which the Roman standards had not yet penetrated. Crassus’ cavalry, too. would have been useless in a Breton wan and were therefore available lor other purposes. It should be remarked that the Aquitanian tribes did not join even in the great revolt ol Book vii; and their connections were far more with Spain than with Gaul, see below, chap. 20: while the Bretons on their side, as Men'vale remarks (vol. 1, p. 343.)‚ took little interest in southern affairs.
